What is an Event?

-- An event is an action that happens in the browser.
Examples:
Button click
Key press
Mouse movement
Page load
Form submit
JavaScript allows us to respond to these actions.

Common JavaScript Events
Event	Description
click	When an element is clicked
dblclick	Double click
mouseover	Mouse enters element
mouseout	Mouse leaves element
keydown	Key is pressed
keyup	Key is released
submit	Form submission
change	Input value changes
load	Page fully loaded
Ways to Add Events
1. Inline Event (Not Recommended)
<button onclick="alert('Clicked')">Click</button>

2. Using DOM Property
const btn = document.getElementById("btn");

btn.onclick = function () {
  alert("Clicked");
};

3. Using addEventListener() (Best Method)
const btn = document.getElementById("btn");
btn.addEventListener("click", function () {
  alert("Clicked");
});

--- Why addEventListener is Best?
- Allows multiple events on same element
Cleaner and professional
Better control (removeEventListener available)
Example: Change Text on Click
<button id="btn">Click Me</button>
<script>
  const btn = document.getElementById("btn");

  btn.addEventListener("click", function () {
    btn.textContent = "Clicked!";
  });
</script>

Event Object

When an event occurs, JavaScript creates an event object.

btn.addEventListener("click", function (event) {
  console.log(event);
});


